definition.value: An octadeca-10,12-dienoic acid having (10E,12Z)-configuration.
An N-acyl-L-homoserine lactone having 3-oxododecanoyl as the acyl substituent.
An aminopyrimidine compound having its amino substituent at the 4-position together with methyl and aminomethyl substituents at the 2- and 5-positions respectively.
An organosulfinic acid that is benzenesulfinic acid in which the hydrogen at position 2 has been replaced by a 2-hydroxyphenyl group.
A peroxide-bridged anthracene substituted at the bridgeheads with methyl and carboxyethyl groups.
A retinoid that is all-trans-retinol in which the hydrogens at position 4 have been replaced by an oxo group.
A dicarboxylic acid monoamide of glutaric acid containing benzene and oxidopiperidine moieties; a transition state analogue hapten used to elicit catalytic antibodies 5C8 and 14B9.

An indolecarboxamide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of indole-2-carboxylic acid with the exocyclic amino group of (3S)-3-amino-1-methyl-5-phenyl-1,3-dihydro-1,4-benzodiazepin-2-one. A cholecystokinin antagonist used for treatment of gastrointestinal disorders.
An N-acylamino acid consisting of 6-aminohexanoic acid bearing an N-(4-hydroxy-3-nitrophenyl)acetyl substituent.
An oxopurine that is guanine which is substituted by an oxo group at position 8.
A nicotinamide dinucleotide comprising NADH having an (S)-2-propylisonicotinoyl group at the 4-position on the dihydronicotinamide ring.
A member of the class of pyrrolidin-2-ones that is pyrrolidin-2-one in which a hydrogen at the 3 pro-S position is replaced by a 3-oxododecanamido group.

A tertiary amino compound that is tamoxifen in which the phenyl group which is in a Z- relationship to the ethyl substituent is hydroxylated at the para- position. It is the active metabolite of tamoxifen.
An organic sodium salt which is the disodium salt of dexamethasone phosphate.
A guanosine 5'-phosphate that is the 2'-O-methyl derivative of guanosine 5'-monophosphate.
A primary aliphatic amine that is ethylamine substituted by two methyl groups at position 1.
A uridine 5'-phosphate that is the 2'-O-methyl derivative of uridine 5'-monophosphate.

A polycyclic ether that is produced by several species of dinoflagellates, and is known to accumulate in both marine sponges and shellfish.  A polyketide, polyether derivative of a C38 fatty acid, it is one of the primary causes of diarrhetic shellfish poisoning (DSP). It is a potent inhibitor of specific protein phosphatases and is known to have a variety of negative effects on cells.
A 9H-purine that is substituted by a (2-hydroxyethyl)nitrilo, benzylnitrilo and a methyl group at positions 2,6 and 9, respectively. It is a  cyclin-dependent kinase inhibitor.
A polyether that consists of undecane in which the carbon atoms at positions 3, 6 and 9 are replaced by oxygen atoms.
A pyrimidine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate that is CMP monomethylated at position O-2'
